RNA-Seq data

In this practice, we are provided RNA-Seq data from 1000 Genomes Project. The raw data contains short reads that correspond to the 500,000th base of chr 1, and the reference genome sequence is the corresponding sectino of hg19 provided by UCSC. The expression analysis data is 8 lymphoblastoid and breast cancer patinets’ data from 1000 Genomes Project and the data are processed by Nex tuxedo pipeline from ChrX. SampleGenes.gtf and SampleReference.fa are UCSC hg19 human reference genome sequence. GTF (Gene Transfer Format) is a format used to hold information about gene structure. It is a tab-delimited text format based on the general feature format (GFF), but contains some additional conventions specific to gene information. They are required for

It looks like this. These are RPKMs of 10 cancer tissues and 10 normal tissues mapped on to 1000 genes. As explained in the previous chapter, RPKM stands for reads per kilobase per million. It’s read count normalized by length to compare expression of different genes, which is then normalized again by total read count in order to compare among different samples. These are the analytic tools to be used:

  1. TopHat: TopHat is the tool to be used in short read alignnment. It uses Bowtie engine to map reads the reference genome. In Bowtie, FM-indexing with backtracking has been successfully applied to approximate string matching/sequence alignment. Refer to this page. In compouter science, FM-index is a compressed full-text substring index based on the Burrows-Wheeler transform, with some similarities to the suffix array. It was created by paolo Ferragina and Giovanni Manzini, who describe it as an opportunistic data structrue as it allows compression of the input text while permitting fast substring queries. The names stands for Full-text index in Minute space. So an FM-index is created by first taking the Burrows-Wheeler transform (BWT) of the input text. For example, the BWT of the string T= “abracadabra$” is “ard$rcaaaabb”, and here it is represented by the matrix \(\textrm{M}\) where each row is a rotation of the text, and the rows have been sorted lexicographicallyl. The transform corresponds to the last column labeled L.
I F L
1 $ abracadabr a
2 a $abracadab r
3 a bra$abraca d
4 a bracadabra $
5 a cadabra$ab r
6 a dabra$abra c
7 b ra$abracad a
8 b racadabra$ a
9 c adabra$abr a
10 d abra$abrac a
11 r a$abracada b
12 r acadabra$a b

The BWT in itself allows for some compresesion with, for instance, move to front and Huffman encoding, but the transform has even more uses. The rows in the matrix are essentially the sorted suffixes of the text and the first column F of the matrix shares similarities with suffix arrays. How the suffix array relates to the BWT lies at the heart of the FM-index. It is possible to make a last-to-first column mapping \(\textrm{LF(i)}\) from an index \(i\) to an index \(j\), such that \(\textrm{F[j] = L[i]}\), with the help of a table \(\textrm{C[c]}\) and a function \(\textrm{Occ(c,k)}\). \(\textrm{C[c]}\) constains the number of occurrences of lexically smaller characters in the text. (number of occurrence). \(\textrm{Occ(c,k)}\) is the number of occurrences of character \(\textrm{c}\) in the prefix \(\textrm{L[1..k]}\). (number of occurrences of the character up until that point.) Last-to-first mapping can be defined as \(\textrm{LF(i) = C[L[i]] + Occ(L[i],i)}\) So FM-index itself is a compression of the string \(\textrm{L}\) together with \(\textrm{C}\) and \(\textrm{Occ}\) in some form, as well as information that maps a selection of indices in \(\textrm{L}\) to positions in the original string \(\textrm{T}\).

  1. Cufflinks: Cufflinks quantifies expression level of aligned short reads. This probably means cufflinks takes bam or sam file format as the input.

  2. HiSAT2: HiSAT2 aligns short reads like TopHat. However, its alignment rate is a lot improved from the traditional BWT/FM indexing because of hierarchical indexing.

  3. StringTie: (Transcript Assembly and Quantification for RNA-seq) StringTie is a fast and highly efficient assembler of RNA-Seq alignments into potential transcripts. Uses different algorithm (a novel network flow algorithm as well as potional de novo assembly step) from what Cufflinks uses, and quantifies the expressed amount of aligned short reads faster than Cufflinks. It assembles and quantitates full-length transcripts representing the multiple splice variants for each gene locus.

  4. StringTie: Performs statistical analysis of aligned transcriptome. Can perform DEG (Differentially Exprsesed Genes), transcriptome structure visualization, and transcriptome annotation.

  5. Gffcompare: Performs GFF file annotations, file comparisons, file merge, etc.

  6. DEGseq: It’s an R package that performs DEG analysis.

II. Original Tuxedo

“Differential gene and transcript expression analysis of RNA-seq experiments with TopHat and Cufflinks” https://www.nature.com/articles/nprot.2012.016

https://m.blog.naver.com/hyeiny119/220940227755

With tuxedo protocol, you can assemble transcriptome from raw sequencing reads and find out stuff about the expression regulation or expression level of your gene of interest. TopHat is a rapid, highly efficient aligner for RNA-seq dadta. Uses bowtie internally. Bowtie2 is a DNA aligner.

Read alignment with TopHat

TopHat is a short read aligner, fast splice junction mapper for RNA-seq reads to reference genome. It aligns RNA-seq reads to mammalian-sized genomes using the ultra high-throughput short read aligner Bowtie, and then anlyzes the mapping resulst to identify splice junctions between exons. For exon mapping, exon needs to be cut into pieces for mapping to take place. This is why we need tuxedo tool. So when you input gtf file, it’s mapped to transcriptome. If reads are not mapped to the transcriptome, they are mapped to the genome and looked for skipped exons. These exons are cut into pieces and mapped to make a whole new geneset file.

The following link is a hell of a site about NGS analysis, with thorough explanation on TopHat pipeline. Aligning RNA-seq data

Also, this is the original article describing the inner workings of TopHat: TopHat: discovering splice junctions with RNA-Seq

1. Input file

TopHat uses reference genome (in this case part of hg19, only chr 1) to align short RNA-seq reads, therefore we need human reference sequence and RNA-seq raw read. .fastq files are the RNA-seq raw reads, and SampleReference.fa is the edited shorter version of UCSC hg19 human genome reference sequence. The files with SampleReference as their prefix are Bowtie index files.

2. Running TopHat

Execute TopHat2.

-o designates output directory, and then you gotta put in reference genome + its index file prefix after that, and then the raw read files of paired-end reads come afterwards.

tophat -o [output_directory/] [SampleReference_prefix] [ShortRead_1_1.Fastq] [ShortRead_1_2.Fastq]

[soh1@x020 RNAPreprocess]$ tophat -o tophat_188462/ Samplereference 188462_1.Fastq 188462_2.Fastq

[soh1@x020 RNAPreprocess]$ tophat -o tophat_188467/ SampleReference 188467_1.Fastq 188467_2.Fastq

Expression Quantification with Cufflinks

1. Input file

Cufflinks takes in these input files: BAM file either from TopHat or HiSAT2 (accepted_hits.bam file from TopHat or AlignedResult.sorted.bam from HiSAT2), and the edited version of UCSC hg19 annotation file called gene.gtf.

2. Running Cufflinks

Usage

cufflinks -G [gene_annotation_file.gtf] -o [output_directory] --no-update-check

-G Go up one directory again into RNAPreprocessing and enter the following command.

cufflinks -G SampleGenes.gtf -o cufflinks_188462 --no-update-check tophat_188462/accepted_hits.bam

cufflinks -G SampleGenes.gtf -o cufflinks_188467 --no-update-check tophat_188467/accepted_hits.bam

You can see that -G means --GTF and it means that you’re going to designate which reference transcript annotation file in GTF file format you’re gonna use. -o designates the output directory, and --no-update-check for not trying to contact server to check for cufflinks update availability. We use the accepted_hits.bam that are products of TopHat operation. The whole process actually takes about 30min. ~ 3 hours depending on file size, but since this is practice the file sizes are minimal.

FPKM is similar to RPKM, but because paired-end reads have two fragments (left fragment, right fragment) per read, however it cannot always exactly equal twice that of RPKM (~x2: it’s about 2 times) due to unmapped fragments (example: only one of the pair is mapped). Therefore we call it fragments per kilobase (of exon model) per millions of mapped reads. Refer to this blog article for clarification. It’s a pretty good read.

3. Master transcriptome using cuffmerge

The main purpose of Cufflinks.cuffmerge is to merge together several Cufflinks assemblies, making it easier to produce an assembly GTF file suitable for use with Cufflinks.cuffdiff. Cufflinks.cuffmerge also runs Cuffcompare in the background and automatically filters out transcribed fragments (transfrags) that are likely to be artifacts. Cuffmerge is basically a “meta-assembler” because it treats the assembled transfrags from Cufflinks the way that Cufflinks treats reads, by merging them together parsimoniously (more succinctly).1

Cuffmerge usage

Usage:
    cuffmerge [Options] <assembly_GTF_list.txt>

Options:
    -h/--help                               Prints the help message and exits
    -o                     <output_dir>     Directory where merged assembly will be written  [ default: ./merged_asm  ]
    -g/--ref-gtf                            An optional "reference" annotation GTF.
    -s/--ref-sequence      <seq_dir>/<seq_fasta> Genomic DNA sequences for the reference.
    --min-isoform-fraction <0-1.0>          Discard isoforms with abundance below this       [ default:           0.05 ]
    -p/--num-threads       <int>            Use this many threads to merge assemblies.       [ default:             1  ]
    --keep-tmp                              Keep all intermediate files during merge

III. New Tuxedo Protocol

“Transcript-level expression analysis of RNA-seq experiments with HISAT, StringTie and Ballgown” https://www.nature.com/articles/nprot.2016.095

http://blog.naver.com/naturelove87/221969005451

So new tuxedo protocol involves HiSAT, StringTie, StringTie –merge, gffcompare, StringTie -eB, Ballgown

RNA-seq analysis can be divided into four steps:

  1. Map reads to genome.

  2. Assemble alignments to whole length reference transcript.

  3. Quantify transcript for each gene.

  4. Calculate expression level difference for all experimental conditions.

So, HiSAT is the aligner that maps RNA-seq reads to the reference genome and finds transcript splice sites (splice junctions). -> HiSAT2 aligns what it can, and for the rest of the unmapped reads, the software automatically finds out if they map to splice junctions that aren’t in the annotation. These alignments are used as input file for StringTie for assembly of transcript. StringTie assembles transcripts and quantify each isoform (expression level). (From reads, it infers what sort of transcript and how many copies of them are present.) After assembly of all the samples, all the set in the assembly are put into StringTie merge. Merge, as its name implies, merges transcripts in GTF/GFF files into a non-redundant set of transcripts. This mode is used in the new differential analysis pipeline to generate a global, unified set of transcripts (isoforms) across multiple RNA-seq samples. This step is necessary because for some samples, only portion of the transcriptome are covered as reads and consequently only a part of them are assembled into transcripts. This results in identical set of transcripts in all samples, without redundant transcripts and covering all unique transcripts. Then with gffcompare you can compare transcripts that are associated with the reference annotation, and also view the statistical report on it. However, because of changed transcript structure, reads need to be assigned again. So with StringTie -eB, reads are assigned again to transcripts and reference annotation. Finally StringTie recalculates the transcript amount and generates a new transcript (read coverage) table. If the -G option (reference annotation) is provided, StringTie will assemble the transfrags (transcribed fragment) from the input GTF files with the reference transcripts. Then all of this, read-count data + transcript + annotation, is passed onto Ballgown, which is the R/Bioconductor package for visualization of differentally expressed genes. Ballgown, with the transcripts and transcript quantitative information, determines differentially expressed gene and transcripts according to experimental condition.

Short Read Alignment w/ HiSAT2

1. Input file

HiSAT2 aligns RNA-seq short reads to reference genome, therefore we need human reference genome sequence and RNA-seq read raw data. Here, we don’t have to prepare index files from Bowtie. We can generate index files through HiSAT2.

2. HiSAT2-build (building binary index of reference genome)

hisat2-build indexer

hisat2-build builds a HISAT2 index from a set of DNA sequences. hisat2-build outputs a set of 6 files with suffixes .1.ht2, .2.ht2, .3.ht2, .4.ht2, .5.ht2, .6.ht2, .7.ht2, and .8.ht2. In the case of a large index these suffixes will have a ht2l termination. These files together constitute the index: they are all that is needed to align reads to that reference. The original sequence FASTA files are no longer used by HISAT2 once the index is built. It uses Karkkainen’s blockwise suffix sorting algorithm (a.k.a. blockwise algorithm) for fast BWT in small space, which allows for a tradeoff between running time and memory usage.

[soh1@x020 RNAPreprocess]$ hisat2-build SampleReference.fa SampleIndex

  Offset rate: 4 (one in 16)

3. Execute HiSAT2 for alignment

We don’t need the .fa file any more, because index files by the name of SampleIndex (prefix) are all we need. -q: It’s fastq file that we’re aligning. -x: This is the index file prefix -1: first paired-end fastq file -2: second paired-end fastq file -S: output file location

hisat2 -q -x SampleIndex -1 188462_1.Fastq -2 188462_2.Fastq -S hisat2_188462/AlignedResult.sam
hisat2 -q -x SampleIndex -1 188467_1.Fastq -2 188467_2.Fastq -S hisat2_188467/AlignedResult.sam

Quantitate Expression Level with StringTie

1. Input file

StringTie’s input also uses TopHat’s output accepted_hits.bam or HiSAT2 ouput AlignedResult.sorted.bam along with UCSC hg19 gene.gtf annotation file. New Tuxedo pipeline uses StringTie.

2. Execute StringTie

The textbook says we have to use AlignedResult.sorted.bam, which of course we don’t have. But remember, we obtained sam files (hisat2_188462/AlignedResult.sam and hisat2_188467/AlignedResult.sam) by aligning the short reads to the reference genome SampleReference.fa. We can use samtools to convert these to bam files and sort them.

Usage:

samtools view -bt ref_list.txt -o aln.bam aln.sam.gz

samtools sort -T /tmp/aln.sorted -o aln.sorted.bam aln.bam

Do this for both hisat2_188462/AlignedResult.sam and hisat2_188467/AlignedResult.sam.

cd hisat2_188462
samtools view -b AlignedResult.sam | samtools sort -T /tmp/AlignedResult.sorted -o AlignedResult.sorted.bam -
cd ../hisat2_188467
samtools view -b AlignedResult.sam | samtools sort -T /tmp/AlignedResult.sorted -o AlignedResult.sorted.bam -

You can also use -Sb option instead of single -b, although -S option that designates the input file format as sam is deprecated. Nowadays, samtools automatically detects the input file format.

-T: temporary files and directory -o: output file name -: input bam file (gets passed on by the pipe operator from samtools view bam format.)

stringtie -G SampleGenes.gtf -l ERR188462 -o ./stringtie_188462/STRG_AlignedResult.gtf hisat2_188462/AlignedResult.sorted.bam
stringtie -G SampleGenes.gtf -l ERR188467 -o ./stringtie_188467/STRG_AlignedResult.gtf hisat2_188467/AlignedResult.sorted.bam

Merge the transcript data of all samples according to the Gene Annotation

All right. So GFF2 format is a flat tab-delimited file, each line of which corresponds to an annotation, or feature. Each line has nine columns and looks like the following:

Chr1 curated CDS 365647 365963 . + 1 Transcript “R119.7”

The actual look into file looks like this:

chr1    unknown exon    14362   14829   .       -       .       gene_id "WASH7P"; gene_name "WASH7P"; transcript_id "NR_024540"; tss_id "TSS7245";

So we’re gonna merge the transcript info into one, nicely unified file that contains all the infos about partial infos of transcripts in each sample. In the merge mode, StringTie takes as input a list of GTF/GFF files and merges/assembles these transcripts into a non-redundant set of transcripts. This mode is used in the new differential analysis pipeline to generate a global, unified set of transcripts (isoforms) across multiple RNA-Seq samples. Usage link: search for “–merge” Output is a merged GTF file with merged gene models, but without any numeric results on coverage, FPKM, and TPM. Therefore, with this merged GTF, StringTie must re-estimate abundances by running it again with the -e option on the original set of alignment files, as illustrated in the figure below. This figure nicely illustrates the whole picture of differential expression analysis pipeline.

Differential Expression Analysis Pipeline
Shorter, faster DE Workflow When No Novel Isoforms Are Found

Novel isoforms in this case mean the assembled transcripts that are present in the samples but are missing from the reference annotation. Therefore, this process only considers the transcripts that are annotated by the reference annotation file (gtf).

Transcript merge usage mode: 
  stringtie --merge [Options] { gtf_list | strg1.gtf ...}
With this option StringTie will assemble transcripts from multiple
input files generating a unified non-redundant set of isoforms. In this mode
the following options are available:
  -G <guide_gff>   reference annotation to include in the merging (GTF/GFF3)
  -o <out_gtf>     output file name for the merged transcripts GTF
                    (default: stdout)
  -m <min_len>     minimum input transcript length to include in the merge
                    (default: 50)
  -c <min_cov>     minimum input transcript coverage to include in the merge
                    (default: 0)
  -F <min_fpkm>    minimum input transcript FPKM to include in the merge
                    (default: 1.0)
  -T <min_tpm>     minimum input transcript TPM to include in the merge
                    (default: 1.0)
  -f <min_iso>     minimum isoform fraction (default: 0.01)
  -g <gap_len>     gap between transcripts to merge together (default: 250)
  -i               keep merged transcripts with retained introns; by default
                   these are not kept unless there is strong evidence for them
  -l <label>       name prefix for output transcripts (default: MSTRG)

So this is what the stringtie --merge usage looks like. Note that { gtf_ list } can be a textfile that contains the list of files to be merged.

  • -G option designates the reference annotation to include in the merging. The file format should either be in GTF of GFF3.

  • -o option designates the output file name for the merged transcripts GTF.

Then you give gtf list as mentioned above as gtf_list, and in this case, is mergelists.txt.

The thing is, the path are not designated correctly, so you must make correction to the textfile mergelists.txt.

For example, the paths in my mergelists.txt was /home/GDA/RNAPreprocess/stringtie_188462/STRG_AlignedResult.gtf and /home/GDA/RNAPreprocess/stringtie_188467/STRG_AlignedResult.gtf, therefore gave errors like below:

Error: cannot find file '/home/GDA/RNAPreprocess/stringtie_188462/STRG_AlignedResult.gtf'

So I changed the directory correctly to where the files were located by vim. Then I executed the following code.

stringtie --merge -G SampleGenes.gtf -o stringtie_merged.gtf mergelists.txt

Compare the detected transcripts with the Reference Genome Annotation w/ gffcompare

Here we can compare gff file and the detected/merged transcript file (gtf) and see how much of the detected transcripts align with the known reference genomic transcripts via sensitivity (the more known transcript, the more sensitivity), and how many are false positives, novel or de novo transcripts, novel exons, novel introns, or new splicing sites, etc via low precision (the less transcript isoforms are clustered together, the more chance of novel transcripts/new splice sites/new exon or introns (or even high false posistive rate)).

stringtie -eB: Align the transcript data to gtf file (merged gtf; stringtie_merged.gtf) and Estimate the Expression Level

Remember that merged gtf (stringtie_merged.gtf) does not contain the expression level data of transcripts, only the transcript names. So we need to re-estimate the abundances (coverage, FPKM, TPM) on the original alignment files.

The usage goes like this:

  • -e only estimate the abundance of given reference transcripts (requires -G)

  • -B enable output of Ballgown table files which will be created in the same directory as the output GTF (requires -G, -o recommended) (SAME DIRECTORY. -b would need desginated)

  • -G reference annotation to use for guiding the assembly process (GTF/GFF3) = the merged GTF.

stringtie <input.bam ..> [options]
stringtie -eB -G stringtie_merged.gtf -o ballgown_188462/ERR_188462.gtf hisat2_188462/AlignedResult.sorted.bam
stringtie -eB -G stringtie_merged.gtf -o ballgown_188467/ERR_188467.gtf hisat2_188467/AlignedResult.sorted.bam

Filter(subset) for transcripts that have variance that is less than 1. The data after filtering is assigned to bg.filt. rowVars is the function that estimates variance for each row (column) in a matrix.

subset usage subset(x, cond, genomesubset = TRUE) ,where x is a ballgown object, cond is the condition on which to subset, and genomesubset=TRUE means subset the ballgown object x to a specific part of the genome. Otherwise, subset x to only include specific samples. TRUE by default. In order to use subset, cond argument as a string representing a logical expression specifying your desired subset. The subset expression can either involve column names of texpr(x, “all”) (if genomesubset is TRUE) or of pData(x) (if genomesubset is FALSE). For example, if you wanted a ballgown object for only chromosome 22, you might call subset(x, “chr == ‘chr22’”). (Be sure to handle quotes within character strings appropriately).

texpr(x, meas="FPKM") usage

Here, texpr is a function that belongs to ball gown that extracts transcript-level expression measurements from ballgown objects. x is a ballgown object, and meas=“FPKM” gives the type of measurement to extract. Can be “cov”, “FPKM”, or “all”. The default is “FPKM”.

bg.filt <- subset(bg.data, "rowVars(texpr(bg.data))>1", genomesubset=TRUE)

Now use ballgown’s stattest function to statistically test whether there are significant difference of gene or transcript level expression according to sex (male or female). stattest performs standard linear model-based statistical analysis. It tests each transcript, gene, exon, or intron in a ballgown object for differential expression, using comparisons of linear models. covariate=“sex” here is the variable that we are dividing the analytic groups into, and adjustvars=c(“population”) pertains to the variables other than this one for correction (covariate adjustment). feature=“gene” takes in whether the unit for statistical test is a gene or a transcript and designates it as gene. getFC=TRUE results in fold change value after adjusting for disrupting variables.

results.genes<-stattest(bg.filt, feature="gene", covariate="sex", adjustvars=c("population"), getFC=TRUE, meas="FPKM")

3. Draw the Gene Expression Level Graph

Visualize the gene expression distribution graph according to sex.

For a more dandy looking graph output, par is for adjusting plot parameters, mar designates the margin and xpd=TRUE means that some elements are going to be drawn outside of the plot region. From bg.data take only the FPKM measurement by using textpr(bg.data, meas="FPKM"). Then add 1 to fpkm and take the whole thing within log2 and make it fpkm. Draw boxplot based on this, color (col) is 1 and 2, and this is designated by the as.numeric(pheno.data$sex). Here you can learn that you can change certain categorical values of a factor (pheno.data$sex is a factor) into numerics. That’s why the factor of age in survival analysis behaved so weirdly by changing factor value of “[Not Available]” into number 1 with as.numeric. In boxplot, “las=2” argument changes the x-label orientation into vertical from horizontal.

par(mar=c(5.6,5,4.1,7), xpd=TRUE)
fpkm = texpr(bg.data, meas="FPKM")
fpkm = log2(fpkm+1) # add 1 so that basal value is not equal to 0, but when fpkm is 0 then log2 itself is 0.
boxplot(fpkm, col=c(1, 2)[as.numeric(pheno.data$sex)], las = 2, ylab="log2(FPKM+1)", space=0.1)
# legend("topright", legend=c("female", "male"), fill=c("blue", "red"), inset=c(-0.25,0)) # when you wanna add blue, red color to legend
legend("topright", legend=c("female", "male"), fill=c(1,2), inset=c(-0.25, 0))

4. Transcript distribution graph for Comparison of Individual Samples

Draw a graph that compares how all the samples are expressing transcripts. First, learn the gene names and transcript names that we’re gonna include in the graph.

ballgown::geneNames(bg.data)[5]
##        5 
## "PLCXD1"
ballgown::transcriptNames(bg.data)[5]
##           5 
## "NM_018390"

What’s the problem with coercion? It says coercion by NA. Numerical expression error was because of damn colon, instead of double colons. Therefore it was recognizing it as a numerical expression.

Now draw the graph.

par(mar=c(5,5,5,5), xpd=TRUE)
plot(fpkm[5,]~pheno.data$sex, border=c(1,2), main=paste(ballgown::geneNames(bg.data)[5],":",ballgown::transcriptNames(bg.data)[5]), pch=19, xlab="Sex", ylab="log2(FPKM+1)")
points(fpkm[5,]~jitter(as.numeric(pheno.data$sex)), col=as.numeric(pheno.data$sex))
legend("topright", legend=c("female", "male"), col=c(1,2), inset=c(-0.25, -0.25), pch=c(1,1))

mar changes margins, xpd changes whether there will be elements outside the plot region onto figure region.

This prints all samples’ log2(FPKM+1) (expression level) of gene PLCXD1’s transcript NM_018390 differing by sex.

6. Draw MA graph

Draw the MA plot of the transcripts that show statistically significant results. An MA plot is an pplication of a Bland-Altman plot for visual representation of genomic data. Now, a Bland-Altman plot itself has a second name, difference plot. It’s a method of data plotting used in analyzing the agreement between two different assays or samples. The plot visualizes the differences between measurements taken in two samples, by transforming the data onto M (log ratio) and A (mean average) scales, then plotting these values. Though originally applied in the context of two channel DNA microarray gene expression data, MA plots are also used to visualize high-throughput sequencing analysis.

results.transcripts$mean <- rowMeans(texpr(bg.filt))

Make a new column in results.transcripts where bg.filt (filtered transcripts that have small p-values) transcript expression level are taken and rowMeans taken, yet again. texpr(bg.filt) is a matrix. And rowMeans results in row-wise mean.

Assumption

RNA sequencing can be modeled as a random sampling process, in which each read is sampled independently and uniformly from every possible nucleotide in the sample.

Model

Under this assumption the number of reads coming from a gene (or transcript isoform) follows a binomial distribution (and could be approximated by a Poisson distribution) (Wang et al, 2010).

MA-plot-based method

MA plot is basically log fold change vs. log average of a gene for two different samples/replicates.

Let C1 and C2 denote the counts of reads mapped to a specific gene obtained from two samples, with Ci ~ binomial(ni, pi), i = 1, 2, where ni denotes the total number of mapped reads and pi the probability of a read coming from that gene. Then \(M = log_2C_1-log_2C_2\), and \(A=(log2C1+log2C2)/2\) It can be proved that under the random sampling assumption the conditoinal distribution of \(M\) given that \(A=a\) (\(a\) is an observation of \(A\)), follows an approximate normal distribution. For each gene on the MA-plot, we do the hypothesis test of \(H_0: \textrm{p}_1=\textrm{p}_2\) versus \(H_1: \textrm{p}_1\ne\textrm{p}_2\). Then a p-value could be assigned based on the conditional normal distribution.

# M = log2C1 - log2C2, and A = (log2C1 + log2C2)/2

Differentially Expressed Gene Analysis

Step 1: MARS (MA-plot-based method with Random Sampling model)

We will fit a simple random sampling model to get the DEGs and will see the effect. The red line of the MA-plot indicates 4-fold local Standard Deviation of M conditioned on A for two samples.

method: method to identify differentially expressed genes. Possible methods are: - “LRT”: Likelihood Ratio Test (Marioni et al. 2008) - “CTR”: Check whether the variation between Technical Replicates can beexplained by the random sampling model (Wang et al. 2009) - “FET”: Fisher’s Exact Test (Joshua et al. 2009) - “MARS”: MA-plot-based method with Random Sampling model (Wang etal. 2009) - “MATR”: MA-plot-based method with Technical Replicates (Wang et al.2009) - “FC”: Fold-Change threshold on MA-plot.

Task 4:

For p-value correction use p.adjust function with “fdr” method and plot both the values to see the difference.

The adjustment methods include the Bonferroni correction (“bonferroni”) in which the p-values are multiplied by the number of comparisons. Less conservative corrections are also included by Holm (1979) (“holm”), Hochberg (1988) (“hochberg”), Hommel (1988) (“hommel”), Benjamini & Hochberg (1995) (“BH” or its alias “fdr”), and Benjamini & Yekutieli (2001) (“BY”), respectively. A pass-through option (“none”) is also included. The set of methods are contained in the p.adjust.methods vector for the benefit of methods that need to have the method as an option and pass it on to p.adjust.

Heatmap

HeatMap is a graphical representation of ofa matrix in color. Let’s combine both the list by row and plot a heatmap. So here the two columns are fold-normalized values of Kidney and Liver samples and the rows are individual DEGs.

Here we will use a red/yellow palette where red indicates downregulated and yellow indicates upregulated.

result_sig_up_kidney_sorted <- result_sig_up_kidney[order(-result_sig_up_kidney$log2_Fold_change_normalized),]
result_sig_down_kidney_sorted <- result_sig_down_kidney[order(result_sig_down_kidney$log2_Fold_change_normalized),]

result_top100 <- rbind ( result_sig_up_kidney_sorted[1:50,], result_sig_down_kidney_sorted[1:50,])

cols <- colorRampPalette(c("red","white","yellow"))(256)

heatmap(as.matrix(result_top100[,c(2,3)]), cexRow=0.3, cexCol=1, labRow=result_top100$GeneNames, keep.dendro = F, Colv=NA, labCol=c("Kidney", "Liver"), col=cols)

geneExpFile <- system.file("extdata", "GeneExpExample5000.txt", package="DEGseq")
geneExpMat<-read.table(file=geneExpFile,header = T,sep = "\t",na.strings="")
colnames(geneExpMat)<-c("EnsemblGeneID", "Chr", "GeneStart", "GeneEnd", "Status",   "ExternalID", "KidneyR1L1","LiverR1L2","KidneyR1L3", "LiverR1L4", "LiverR1L6", "KidneyR1L7", "LiverR1L8", "LiverR2L1", "KidneyR2L2", "LiverR2L3","KidneyR2L4", "KidneyR2L6", "LiverR2L7", "KidneyR2L8")

Now can we pull out the data for those 100 selected genes from this file? Can we make a heatmap for this 100 genes ploting all 14 samples? Use the same colour palette for it and this time we also want a dendogram for x-axis.
